3. How to test it

You have two easy choices:

Choice A: Using your SD Card (The "MUSIC.BIN" method)

Since your bootloader already searches for a file and copies it to 0x80000000, and then OpenSBI jumps to 0x80200000, we can cheat:

Rename payload.bin to MUSIC.BIN.

In your bootloader assembly, change the jump logic so that it loads OpenSBI first to 0x80000000, and then loads payload.bin to 0x80200000.

Or, more simply, just use the FW_PAYLOAD option in OpenSBI.

Choice B: Embedding into OpenSBI (The Best Way)

The generic platform supports a "Payload." This merges your code into the OpenSBI image.

Move your payload.bin to the OpenSBI folder.

Run this make command:

code
Bash
download
content_copy
expand_less
make CROSS_COMPILE=... \
     PLATFORM=generic \
     FW_TEXT_START=0x80000000 \
     FW_PAYLOAD=y \
     FW_PAYLOAD_PATH=payload.bin \
     FW_FDT_PATH=my_board.dtb

This creates a large fw_payload.bin.

Copy fw_payload.bin to your SD card.

In your bootloader, copy this file to 0x80000000 and jump to 0x80000000.

What to expect on the screen:

When you boot, you will see the standard OpenSBI banner, then at the very bottom, you should see:

code
Text
download
content_copy
expand_less
...
Boot HART MEDELEG : 0x000000000000b109
S VM ON TRAP

If you see S: Privilege levels are working.

If you see VM ON: Your isr_router (MMU software walker) in ROM is working perfectly and correctly refilled the TLB!

If you see TRAP: Your hardware's interrupt delegation is working.

If all three appear, your SoC is 100% ready for the Linux Kernel.
